I'm not a member at Hyperion, but I think, I can also say something to this
topic.
I am very happy, that there are pure PPC boards available in near future
(don't know, how near).
As a programmer, I'm really pissed off by the wide range of system
configuration. If you want to write time critical appz or games, you have
to use your own custom routines for displaying graphic or make other things
happen. As a coder I have to run circles around every limitaion the
"modern" amiga system if offering. 
If you want to write a programm, you are forced to decide your level of
hardware support: 
"Should I write some code for AGA, or gfx card only? May I support pure 68k
systems, or is my minimum configuration a PPC system? Is it better to make
an AHI routine only, or is the speed gain with paula output effording the
developing/time costs? Next time I should consider mediator.library before
writing some data to gfx card?"
It is not only the old argument: "I want get it running on my system! It may
run with 1 fps, but I want support for my hardware!". It is a pain to make
the codes more complex, just for keeping the old configs alive. 
Of course you can make it the easy way - use the OS functions. But that is
decreasing performance in most cases. It will slow down the speed on slow
hardware, and won't reach the speed on more decent hardware, as a custom
code could do.
IIRC, some years ago, shortly after anouncing Warp3D, some people where
asking for software Warp3D! Only for getting a game running on a non-3D
Amiga.

With a really new and clear OS with a retargable graphic and audio
interface, programming would become a lot easier. I could live without
VP-code, if I have a fixed and fast API for my programm calls. AT this
moment I have the feeling, my programms are written for three different
computer systems, just for supporting the actual present Amiga configs.

If the OS4 is finished and running on the AmigaOne board or even on PegasOS,
then some people could start to write some hardware layer, that runs on
existing Phase5 cards. I dont wanna see only one compromise, that is
founded on today systems - like "custom chip usage" or "68k code execution
on 68k". Perhaps there will be this kind of layer for today ppc-cards, but
then don't blame the appz and games, if they dont run fast enough.
I think, the jump from ppc-hardware now used to a ppc-only mainboard will be
like the jump from 030 to 060. And if there is an emulation of the AmigaOne
board/system on an existing Amiga, then it would be like emulating a
603/604 card on a 030 system! And writing such an emulation or hardware
layer could be more complex, than writing an OS for the AmigaOne board. 

It is not only the higher clocked G3/G4, that will gain much speed, it also
the L2 cache, the PC100/133 RAM interface. On the BlizzardPPC/CyberStormPPC
cards, the PPCs are "downgraded" to work with 040/060 and to solve the
context switching problem. PS/2 rams at 60ns are nothing compared to 10ns
or 7ns rams - not to mention (or be able to use) DDR rams. That's not
simply some percent, that are ages for a CPU.

On the other hand, really speedy hardware could tend to make the developers
lazy. As I sad before, sometimes you have to do a huge optimization in your
code, to get the programm running at decent speed. Sometimes you have to
find and use incredible tricks, just to get a little more speed :\
With the new boards available for developing appz and games, I doubt, that
this kind of "coding magic" will continue. Who cares, if HereticII is then
running on 120 fps or 90 fps? And all the optimizations for the classic
machines wouldn't even pay the time to think about them.

I'm happy, that AmigaInc does not care about the old machines, when they are
designing their new OS4. A clear cut is better than still having AGA
support in 2005. But I can also understand the people, who cant afford a
new PPC mainboard. For a well made future operating system, they will have
to pay the price of patience (until AmigaOne emulation is released - if it
is released) and slow programs, if they really want to run OS4 programs.
Noone will force the people, to buy and use the new systems. You can stick
forever with dual board cards, attatched PCI cards (and CPU-modules
attatched to them). If you are lucky, there are releases/ports of new OS4
games for classic Amigas.

The new system (OS4, AmigaOne/PegasOS) offers backwards compatibility in a
fair range (except custom chips), but todays systems can give no, or just
small upwards compatibility.

Regards,
