@node 08496.004
Subject: Re: opinion
From: Daniel Bindel <d_bindel@gmx.net>
Date: Fri, 06 Apr 2001 00:12:14 +0200

> Thank you for your very clear explication !
> 
> I don't think it is possible to contradict all your arguments.

Want some examples in a real worlds program?

Let's look at the graphic output, that you want to do. First question, in
what format are your data, planar, or chunky? Planar data would be better
to handle with AGA, because you only need then to copy them to the CHIP
RAM. But when the user selects a gfx screen, you have to do planar2chunky
conversion, that is eating cpu-time. But planar is not good, for doing easy
drawing calls in your frame buffer, so you will use chunky gfx in your
program. OK, but then a c2p routine is needed, for AGA users. Your luck is,
that c2p codes are spread widely and they are optimized a lot. But why
should you even do a conversion, if there would exist only one way, to
handle/deliver graphic data?
Next thing is color palette upload on 8 bit screens and syncronisation with
the VBL. Color update depends on a proper sync, because every change is
visible immediately on screen. Only possible method seem to be the
WaitBOVP(), function provided by graphics.library and patched by gfx
system. The "normal" AmigaOS WaitTOF() is locked to the internal VBL
interrupt, that is generated by AGA - not by your gfx card. When you have
finally your sync to the VBL of the gfx card, the next surprise is the
terrible slow color update for nearly every card/gfx system. The VBL is the
point, when gfx card reaches bottom of screen and pauses a little, before
start writing the analog signal at top of screen. In this pause you have to
upload all your new color palette. Custom chips can upload the whole 256
colors inside this VBL, gfx cards achieve 30%-75% of the colors. So the gfx
system is still uploading the new colors to the card, while this is
allready writing to the monitor - the resulting picture is tending from
"funny" to "strange". When you are playing an animation with changing color
palettes, this limitation can stop your development. It cost me 3 month, to
find a way around this fact.
Audio is nice, when you know how to use it. Using AHI for playback streams
of audio data is something like setting up a device and IORequest. Sadly
AHI is not as fast as a self made paula code (measured on
44.1kHz/16bit/stereo sound). With downsampling the same source in realtime,
paula is about 30-50% faster (14 bit/22.1kHz). But using paula with the
same device/IORequest interface is not very good, bacause only one channel
can be started with one call. Best way to control paula seems to be direct
audio-interrupt handlers.
Second limitation of AHI seems to be the unability to handle FIFO audio
buffers. I tried it in several ways, but didn't get a result. So if you use
flexible FIFO buffers, you have to make a FIFO-DoubleBuffer routine,
swapping the memory around. But perhaps I overlooked something, and serving
FIFO buffers to AHI is as easy as eating pancakes?
Device/harddisk/CD-ROm speed. Actual filesystems like FFS and CDROM systems
are awful, when handling big files. The seeking times are becoming bigger
and bigger, when you are going through the file to it's end. A few month
ago, I tried to copy several thousand files from CDROM to harddisk. At the
last files, it took 5 seconds, to copy a 80kB file! Same is for big files
under FFS. When you write or read to/from a big file, avoid Seek() to place
the pointer in the file. Read everything in one direction, or calculate
everything, before you are writing something. Frequently Seeks() will kill
every performance. But they are needed, to set the correct position or
parse data files. 
To the 68k vs. PPC context switches have allready been said a lot. Avoiding
OS calls from the PPC side, can limit you a lot. You have to make allmost
all disk-loading routines on the 68k side, for beeing faster as a pure PPC
code. After loading all needed data to memory, you can switch to ppc and
process them. The problem would be, that you don't allways know, how much
and what data you need. Perhaps inside the data processing/decoding, you
will see, that there are additional information from the file needed. Your
programm structure will also become more complicated, because you must hold
all different data blocks in memory, before you switch to ppc.

> I can add that all curent PPC proggz and games (on BPPC/CPPC cards)
> will benefits from the optimizations made to run as fast as possible.

Of course, after optimizing them, they are faster. But many optimizations
are not needed, if you dont have to care about all the things, that could
make your programm slower then needed. Most times the goal of optimization
is not making it faster, but avoiding all the "slowdown" traps, that are
hidden in the Amiga system. 
If you are finishing an algorithm or a program in a normal matter - the code
is doing the things, it was build for - you take your "Amiga"-experience
and rewrite some smaller or even bigger parts of the code, because you
know, that you could get in heavy or light trouble with the Amiga
hardware/software.
Developing time is developing costs. Seeking the weak points in a program,
that would at this point ready to ship on other computer systems, is
perhaps a honourable task, but it is an additional one. You will improve
your coding skills for Amiga, that is the only profit.

The way, how todays ppc and gfx-card hardware is implemented into the 1992's
original motherbaords and the OS software, is not really clean. You can
call it "cool" and "astounding". I would also give the "Mac Gyver Award" to
the Amiga, because it's ability, to extend it to the edges is IMHO unique
in the computers world. Adding a Porsche motor to a VW beatle is also cool,
but will give you in addition more problems, when you use it.

This hardware concept can not be continued for the future. The software
concepts, that control this "patched" hardware, will also becoming more
complicated. The results are speed losses, due to compromises with old
systems, or incompatibily to older or even parallel developed systems. I
fear, that this parallel incompatibility is most hurting one - see PowerUp,
WarpUP. A strong leading force is needed, to give the direction of new
hardware. Elsewere, there will be some kind of "evolution" - only the most
spreaded hardware solution will survive/get software support. 
The disadvantage of a central leadingship, is the ability, to make really
bad mistakes - as seen in the past.

> Heretic2, Shogo, ..... will be more optimized than original vesions on PC.

"Optimized" is related to the environment, the thing is existing in. A fish
optimized to underwater breathing would die on land. I don't know, if
HereticII will gain that speed improvment on a PC, if you would port it
back to Windows.
So optimizing games on an Amiga systems, is in one way optimizing the main
algorithm. That includes all the steps, that are done, to achieve a defined
result. The other part is to adapt some parts of the program, so that it
doesn't fall into one of the Amiga "traps". You will then go through the
program and think "I should avoid this thing. Better do this part with some
other calls. Find some trick, how to do this work in a completelly
different way."
The result is of course faster and "impressive", because it would normally
impossible, to achieve that speed.
If you could simply take the sources of a PC game and recompile it, I think,
Shogo would have been released years before.

