The effect of experience can be very big. When you know, how a CPu works (a
specific or even in general) you can design your algorithms in a way, that
there are only very few and fast instructions are needed, to make it
working. It is no secret, that every modern CPU is slowed down, if you make
intensive use of 'branch' instructions (decision points, to control the
instruction flow of a program). So building an algorithm in C, that
includes many loops and 'if's inside each other is not as good as an
'unrolled' code. This one would execute all instructions linear and would
have the loop instruction only at the end. Building your algorithms on
propper aligned data types (LONG better than BYTE) will also speed up a
little.
But sadly these basic lessons of software developing are not very popular in
times when VisualBasic (arghhhh, eeek, baaaeeeeh) is seen as an acceptable
way to write programs.
So I would say, that the Amiga's programmers 'mindset' is not only a myth.
If you learn to drive with a bicycle as fast as a motorbike - how fast will
you be with a car?
I hope, that old programmers remember the good tricks, how to make a program
really fast on a machine.

As for modern OS'. There could be direct connection between the features of
an OS and the speed that it is demanding. Virtual memory and memory
protection on Windows seems to rely on relicts from the stone age. There
was the obsolete feature of a limited adressible memory area in DOS. More
memory could only addressed, with the help of paging technology. In that
way old and new programs could run on the same machine. The other problem
was doing multitasking with programs, that never heard about that. They
simply thought, they could use the memory from pointer 0 and upwards. They
where given separate memory's that looked from the program's view as it
would start from 0 - but was redirected by OS and MMU to physical memory.
>From this point (redirection and mem-paging) it was not a far step to
virtual memory and mem protection. 
The 'failure' of Amiga was, that it has a much better technology. From the
early prototypes it has full access to the complete memory and all programs
accept the rules for multitasking system (at least theoretical :)
Adding new features to the OS would make it a little bit slower, as every
read/write access by programs should be checked, if they are correct. BTW,
there is allready a preparation for mem protection in Amiga OS. You can
tell the system at memory allocation, if this block is your private, or
public available. But of course this information is not yet used by Amiga
OS 1.2 - 3.9 ;)
An OS, that is doing nearly nothing, would be the fastes - but perhaps not
the most loved one. But also the way, how to do necessary operations, is
important for the speed. I believe, AmigaOS can do things like task and
memory handling very effective, because it does not care about "stone age"
compromises.  

> The same is the mad Amiga One dream... ...not conuting the VERY IMPORTANT
> fact, that these messages and project's are being there for quite a long
> time and NONE of these fake rumors get's materialized.

Yeah, there have been much promises from Amiga leadership. And since 1994
(CD32?) none of these skyscraping projects have been realized. But this
time, I feel, they are very close to something, that can be sold and used.
Perhaps, because they didn't set their targets too high. The boards from
Eytech and bPlan (prototype?) are real and physical, so a new and fast home
for the Amiga is in near future. It's like these two cute cartoon mice
'Pinky and Brain'. They try every evening, to conquer the world and become
'world's leader'. They can never relize their fantastic plans, but after
every failure, Pinky asks Brain "What do we do next evening?" - "The same
as we do every evening - we try to rule the world". Plan No. 4 (?) of
Amiga, to come back to top of computers, is IMHO the most promising one ;)

