On Thursday 19 April 2001 21:18, PN wrote:

> 400MB! What the hell is there are going on?

Today's video games can do that, simply because of the existance of virtual 
memory. If you have the chance, check out the E3 video of Halo. Another good 
example is Necron. Those games have *HUGE* gaming worlds, with very 
high-detailed characters. Also, today's PC games are aimed at resolutions of 
1024x768; you can't use 64x64 textures on that screen size without looking 
blocky. 

So textures get bigger. In fact, Quake 3's ground textures can be as large as 
2048x2048. 16 megs per texture. 

Unreal Tournament uses three 256x256 skin textures per model. That's 768k per 
model on skins alone, left alone the geometry which can easily get beyond the 
three megabytes barrier. The biggest Textures in Heretic II where 256x256 in 
size (for example, the Dolphin pattern in the reptilian city, Andoria).

A 400 MB memory footprint is feasable at the moment. Future games will 
require more. That is the reason why today you need at least 128 megs in your 
Windows box to play anywhere near a comfortable swapping level.

This is also the reason why porting new games is considerably more difficult 
that porting older games.

Regards,
-- 
