> Mmmm...If they really had time to work on this game, I'd rather see the
> little glitches in texture mapping/lightning corrected.

Glitches in texture mapping? I don't know what you mean. If you are talking 
about the flickering in certain fireballs and explosions, this comes from the 
CPU and graphics chip working at the same time.

About the lightning, the effect you see is called the "gouraud shading 
lightning variance" problem. This is inherent when you use gouraud shading. 
The problem is that gouraud shading only samples the light values at the 
corner points and then interpolates these. However, trianges/stuff is 
rendered line by line, so rotating a polygon can cause great disturbance in 
the force^H^H^H^H^H lightning...

There are only three possible solutions for that that immediately come to my 
mind:

- Subdivide the polygons. Smaller polygons do not suffer so severely under 
the lightning variance.

- Use lightmaps as in Quake. This would require a preprocessor, and you would 
still need to account for dynamic light (Descent, BTW, was the first game 
ever that used moving dynamic lightning).

- Use GeForce pixel shaders :-)

